{"slideshow_credits": null, "snippet": "As an inmate, I saw the way sexual assault is tacitly accepted as part of the punishment.", "abstract": "Op-Ed article by author Chandra Bozelko deplores culture of sexual abuse in America's prisons, which continues after 2003 passage of Prison Rape Elimination Act and results in sexual abuse of 80,000 men and women yearly; notes only New Hampshire and New Jersey have fully complied with law and six Republican governors have refused or neglected to comply; contends compliance is ultimately far less expensive than non compliance and is important step toward end of shameful status quo.", "section_name": "Opinion", "print_page": "19", "document_type": "article", "byline": {"person": [{"firstname": "Chandra", "role": "reported", "lastname": "BOZELKO", "rank": 1, "organization": ""}], "original": "By CHANDRA BOZELKO", "contributor": ""}, "web_url": "http://www.nytimes.com/2015/04/18/opinion/why-we-let-prison-rape-go-on.html", "lead_paragraph": "As an inmate, I saw the way sexual assault is tacitly accepted as part of the punishment.", "headline": {"print_headline": "Why We Let Prison Rape Go On", "main": "Why We Let Prison Rape Go On", "content_kicker": "Op-Ed Contributor", "kicker": "Op-Ed Contributor"}, "_id": "5531a0b538f0d86ab80c2333", "word_count": "876", "multimedia": [{"height": 126, "url": "images/2015/04/18/opinion/18Bozelko/18Bozelko-thumbWide.jpg", "legacy": {"wideheight": "126", "wide": "images/2015/04/18/opinion/18Bozelko/18Bozelko-thumbWide.jpg", "widewidth": "190"}, "subtype": "wide", "width": 190, "type": "image"}, {"height": 710, "url": "images/2015/04/18/opinion/18Bozelko/18Bozelko-articleLarge.jpg", "legacy": {"xlarge": "images/2015/04/18/opinion/18Bozelko/18Bozelko-articleLarge.jpg", "xlargewidth": "600", "xlargeheight": "710"}, "subtype": "xlarge", "width": 600, "type": "image"}, {"height": 75, "url": "images/2015/04/18/opinion/18Bozelko/18Bozelko-thumbStandard.jpg", "legacy": {"thumbnail": "images/2015/04/18/o